{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregation step we have global P95 per component-KPI stored in kernel variable agg_metric, and we confirmed metrics, traces, and logs are loaded. Next, per the diagnosis workflow we should use metrics to narrow candidate components and time windows. Specifically, we must detect metric anomalies within the incident window (2021-03-10 22:00 to 22:30 UTC+8) by comparing each metric point in that window against the global P95 computed from the full series (stored in agg_metric).\n\nWhat to derive next: for each component-KPI, count how many points in the incident window exceed the global P95, the earliest anomaly timestamp in the window, the maximum observed value in the window, and the maximum breach ratio (max_value / p95). This will give a ranked, bounded list of candidate faulty component-KPIs to investigate with traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv to the time range '2021-03-10 22:00:00' to '2021-03-10 22:30:00' in UTC+8. Join these filtered rows with the precomputed agg_metric (on cmdb_id and kpi_name) to get the global p95 for each component-KPI. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count = count of rows where value >= p95, earliest_anom_ts = earliest timestamp among those anomaly rows, max_value within the time window, and max_over_p95_ratio = max_value / p95. Keep only groups with anomaly_count > 0. Return the top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count descending, showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_ts, max_value, p95, max_over_p95_ratio. Also store the resulting table in a kernel variable named metric_anomalies for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold calculation and anomaly detection for metrics and traces within the incident window (2021-03-10 22:00–22:30 UTC+8). Metric anomalies show many (cmdb_id,kpi) groups with full-window breaches (anomaly_count = 31) beginning at 2021-03-10 22:00:00+08:00 — notably Tomcat03 (request/error/session KPIs) and IG01 (JVM memory KPIs). Trace anomalies show elevated durations/row_counts on several docker nodes (dockerB2 with 16 minutes of duration_p95 anomalies, dockerA2/A1 with a few anomalies), and some Tomcat->MG trace anomalies (Tomcat02, Tomcat04). Logs and error_logs are not showing error lines (error_logs empty; log.error_count mostly zero).\n\nWhat remains: identify actual faults (consecutive anomaly sub-series) per KPI to obtain precise fault start times and severity, then use traces to determine causal relationships (downstream faulty service) and logs to refine reason. The immediate next step is to convert the metric anomalies into explicit \"fault\" intervals (consecutive minutes where metric >= its global P95), filter out isolated spikes, and report the earliest fault start times and severity metrics so we can prioritize components for trace/log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the precomputed agg_metric (global p95 per cmdb_id/kpi_name), consider only the (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups present in metric_anomalies. For each such group, extract all metric points within 2021-03-10 22:00:00 to 2021-03-10 22:30:00 (UTC+8), sort by timestamp, and detect consecutive segments where value >= p95. Define \"consecutive\" as adjacent timestamps separated by exactly 60 seconds. For each consecutive segment (a candidate fault) compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_ts, fault_end_ts, rows_count (minutes), duration_minutes, max_value (within segment), p95, max_over_p95_ratio = max_value / p95. Filter out segments with rows_count < 3 (treat as isolated noise). Return the top 20 fault segments sorted by rows_count desc then max_over_p95_ratio desc, showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_ts, fault_end_ts, rows_count, duration_minutes, max_value, p95, max_over_p95_ratio. Also store the full resulting table in a kernel variable named metric_faults for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have identified many persistent metric faults spanning the entire 31-minute window (22:00–22:30) across multiple components (IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02, Mysql01/02, Redis01/02, ServiceTest*, Tomcat03, etc.). Many of these metric faults simply equal their global P95 (ratio ≈1.0), which makes it hard to pick a single decisive root cause from metrics alone. Trace anomalies are more discriminative: dockerB2 shows frequent duration_p95 anomalies starting at 22:00 (16 minutes), dockerA2 shows several high-ratio anomalies (some >2x p95) around 22:01 and 22:10–22:12, and there are a few Tomcat->MG trace anomalies (Tomcat02, Tomcat04) at early times (22:01, 22:07). Logs and error_logs contained no error lines to help.\n\nWhat this implies: there are multiple concurrent sustained metric deviations across many nodes/services (some possibly benign due to thresholding), while traces show localized performance spikes on dockerA2/dockerB2 and some Tomcat services. To map the two recorded failures to concrete root causes we need to (a) consolidate metric and trace faults by component, (b) extract the earliest anomalous timestamp per component and the maximum severity (max_over_p95_ratio) per source (metric vs trace), and (c) sort candidates by earliest occurrence to identify distinct failure start times (likely two different timestamps). This will yield a short ranked candidate list to inspect with logs/traces in the next step.\n\nTherefore the next step is to produce a compact per-component candidate summary combining metric_faults and trace_anomalies (earliest times and peak severity) so we can identify the two earliest, most severe candidate faults for root-cause localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variables metric_faults and trace_anomalies, produce a compact candidate summary aggregated by cmdb_id with these fields: earliest_metric_fault_start = minimum fault_start_ts from metric_faults for that cmdb_id (or NULL if none), earliest_trace_anom_ts = minimum earliest_anom_ts from trace_anomalies for that cmdb_id (or NULL if none), overall_earliest = minimum of the two timestamps (ignore NULLs), max_metric_ratio = maximum max_over_p95_ratio from metric_faults for that cmdb_id (or NaN if none), max_trace_ratio = maximum max_over_p95_ratio from trace_anomalies for that cmdb_id (or NaN if none), metric_fault_count = count of metric_fault segments for that cmdb_id, trace_anom_count = count of trace_anomaly groups for that cmdb_id. Return the top 20 rows sorted by overall_earliest ascending (earliest first). Also store the resulting table in a kernel variable named candidate_components. Keep output compact and bounded (max 20 rows, selected columns only)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification steps. Metric analysis produced many persistent faults across many components (many groups equal their P95 for the entire window). Trace anomalies narrowed candidates to a smaller set (dockerA1/A2/B2, MG01/02, Tomcat01–04, etc.) and provided more discriminative severity/timing (dockerB2: 16 minutes starting 22:00; dockerA2: high-ratio spikes around 22:01 and 22:10–22:12; Tomcat02/Tomcat04 trace anomalies at ~22:01 and ~22:07). Candidate aggregation shows several components with both metric faults and trace anomalies (IG01, Tomcat01–04) — these are high priority. However, metrics alone are ambiguous because many groups simply equal global P95 (ratio ≈1.0). To localize the root cause(s) for the two recorded failures we must use traces to identify downstream faulty services in call chains: find trace anomaly records where the trace direction indicates calls to another service/container and check whether that target is also metric-faulty. This will let us identify the most-downstream faulty component(s) and their earliest anomalous timestamp(s), separating possibly two distinct failures if they occur in different call chains/times. Logs contain no errors and error_logs are empty, so traces + metrics are our primary signals for localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel tables trace_anomalies and metric_faults, examine trace anomalies involving the top candidate components: {IG01, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, dockerA1, dockerA2, dockerB1, dockerB2, MG01, MG02, apache01, apache02}. For trace_anomalies rows where trace_name contains 'to_' or 'from_', extract the counterpart component name embedded in the trace_name (e.g., trace.to_MG02.* => counterpart = MG02; trace.from_Tomcat02.* => counterpart = Tomcat02). For each such trace anomaly produce a compact row with columns: source_cmdb = cmdb_id (the row's cmdb_id), trace_name, counterpart_cmdb (parsed), anomaly_count, earliest_anom_ts, max_value, p95, max_over_p95_ratio, counterpart_has_metric_fault (True if counterpart_cmdb appears in metric_faults, else False), counterpart_earliest_metric_fault (the earliest fault_start_ts for counterpart_cmdb from metric_faults, or NaT). Return at most top 20 rows sorted by earliest_anom_ts ascending. Also store the resulting table in a kernel variable named trace_links for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metrics, traces, and logs across the incident window and identified two dominant combined-anomaly minutes: 2021-03-10 22:02:00+08:00 (largest combined count, dominated by metric anomalies) and 2021-03-10 22:20:00+08:00 (large combined count with notable trace involvement). At 22:02 the top affected components by metric anomaly rows are Mysql02, Mysql01, Redis02, Redis01 and Tomcat03; representative KPIs point to MySQL I/O (Innodb data written / binlog / stmt cache), filesystem/disk and memory metrics. Trace anomalies at 22:02 show MG02↔dockerA* and Tomcat↔IG links with modest ratios; logs show high row_count but no error_count spikes. At 22:20 the top components again include Mysql01/02, Redis01/02, MG01/02 and Tomcat03 with KPIs indicating disk I/O, JVM memory/heap, and MySQL activity; trace anomalies at 22:20 often reference a counterpart labelled \"root\" (likely a naming/endpoint artifact) with modest ratios. From the rules, root cause localization requires identifying the most-downstream faulty component in traces that is also metric-faulty and determining the first timestamp of its fault. To finalize root cause for each of the two failures we need per-component KPI details at those exact timestamps to determine the resource/reason (e.g., disk I/O, JVM heap/OOM, CPU, network).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For timestamp 2021-03-10 22:02:00+08:00, extract all metric rows from metric.csv for these components: Mysql02, Mysql01, Redis02, Redis01, Tomcat03. Join each row with agg_metric (on cmdb_id and kpi_name) to obtain the global p95. For each returned row include columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95, ratio = value / p95 (handle p95==0 accordingly). Return up to 200 rows sorted by cmdb_id then by descending ratio, and store the full result in a kernel variable named detailed_metrics_2202."
}

